Good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:03.910 --> 00:00:05.480
Thank you for coming today.

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:08.600
So today we have a
very special guest.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:11.290
Just a little bit of
background on Ruth.

00:00:11.290 --> 00:00:14.830
So Ruth Sherman works with
top CEOs, celebrities,

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:16.750
and small-business
entrepreneurs to help

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:19.340
them become charismatic
speakers, presenters,

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:21.315
and video and media darlings.

00:00:21.315 --> 00:00:23.690
Ruth has worked with some of
the world's largest and most

00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:27.800
prestigious companies,
top CEOs, movie stars,

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:29.470
international celebrities.

00:00:29.470 --> 00:00:32.549
Four of her clients have
won Oscars, and one of them

00:00:32.549 --> 00:00:34.920
has won the Pulitzer Prize.

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:37.550
Her many film project include
"Dallas Buyer's Club,"

00:00:37.550 --> 00:00:39.940
"Insidious: Chapter
3," her first horror

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:43.840
film, and the recently-opened
"Suffragette" and "Trumbo."

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:46.290
She loves getting
paid to watch movies.

00:00:46.290 --> 00:00:48.500
But you don't have to be
famous to work with Ruth,

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:50.740
and she's here today with
us, so that's awesome.

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:53.110
Her new book, "Speakrets"--
which is outside.

00:00:53.110 --> 00:00:54.340
Everybody should grab a copy.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:54.970
It's amazing.

00:00:54.970 --> 00:00:59.180
I read it cover to cover-- "The
30 Best, Most Effective, Most

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:02.180
Overlooked Marketing and
Personal Branding Essentials"

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:05.560
is the name of her book, is
available on Amazon and just

00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:07.060
outside this room.

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:09.220
She's also a
widely-quoted expert

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:12.010
on political communication
who knows that the better

00:01:12.010 --> 00:01:13.870
communicator always wins.

00:01:13.870 --> 00:01:17.520
Her first career was as one of
a handful of successful New York

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:19.380
jingle-singers,
whose voice was heard

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:23.380
around the world on commercials
such as Coca-Cola, Ford,

00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:25.460
Michelob, and Clairol,
and as a backup singer

00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:27.010
for major recording artists.

00:01:27.010 --> 00:01:30.080
Ruth holds a Master's Degree
in Speech and Interpersonal

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.150
Communication from NYU.

00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:33.734
Everybody please
welcome Ruth Sherman.

00:01:33.734 --> 00:01:34.733
RUTH SHERMAN: Thank you.

00:01:34.733 --> 00:01:35.560
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:37.880
Thanks, [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:37.880 --> 00:01:39.440
Thank you.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:41.370
First things first.

00:01:41.370 --> 00:01:44.970
In order for us to
have this discussion,

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:47.900
you've got to leave your
politics at the door.

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:52.200
Do I have your pledge
that you'll do that?

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:52.740
Yes?

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:53.505
Shake your head.

00:01:53.505 --> 00:01:54.380
Just shake your head.

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:55.637
Yes. [LAUGHTER]

00:01:55.637 --> 00:01:57.470
This is the hardest
thing to do, by the way.

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:01.030
It is very hard to not have
opinions about candidates,

00:02:01.030 --> 00:02:02.700
because what I'm doing
today, of course,

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:06.400
is using them to talk about
speaking and communication,

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:10.180
because we're in the midst of
this presidential campaign.

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:14.390
So this is one presentation
that I roll out every four years

00:02:14.390 --> 00:02:17.330
because I think it's so
fascinating to watch how

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:20.810
these candidates communicate
and influence our vote,

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:22.850
or, at least, try to.

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:24.490
So leave your
politics at the door.

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:27.810
The only way that I know that
I am doing it right, when I get

00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:30.070
interviewed by
media, because they

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:34.410
call me to ask me
what do I think

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:37.800
about what the
candidates are doing,

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.710
and who is doing a good
job, and who might win,

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:42.910
which I don't predict quite yet.

00:02:42.910 --> 00:02:45.494
They always ask me, and I
always have to be very careful.

00:02:45.494 --> 00:02:47.160
We all have our biases,
and the only way

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:49.201
I know I'm doing it right
is when I get hate-mail

00:02:49.201 --> 00:02:51.650
from both sides. [LAUGHTER] OK?

00:02:51.650 --> 00:02:52.420
All right.

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:55.750
So there are a couple of reasons
that I do this presentation

00:02:55.750 --> 00:02:57.050
every few years.

00:02:57.050 --> 00:03:00.520
The first reason is that
I think it's important.

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:02.420
As an expert in
communication, and somebody

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:04.890
who's doing this for
a very long time,

00:03:04.890 --> 00:03:10.000
I think it's my civic
duty to inform the voters,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.360
and people who come
to my presentations,

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:15.760
about just how the candidates
use these communications

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:17.770
techniques to
influence our vote,

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.570
as I mentioned a moment ago.

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:22.680
The second reason is
because this is a master

00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:23.900
class in public speaking.

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:28.020
I was talking to a few of you
here before we got started.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:30.800
And it's important to
pay attention to this,

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:35.720
because we can learn what to do,
and, of course, what not to do.

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:39.480
And it happens in every
single-- it's constant.

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:41.230
It's wallpaper.

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:44.040
You are bombarded
with opportunities

00:03:44.040 --> 00:03:47.240
to see these people, and
to watch them, and to learn

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:50.220
by simply observing them.

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:53.980
So those are the two reasons
that I do this presentation.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:56.230
So today we'll make
some connections

00:03:56.230 --> 00:03:58.960
between what they
do and what you

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:02.380
can do to advance in your
careers and in your businesses.

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:05.660
And so here they are.

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:08.260
This was the second
debate, I think,

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:09.710
and some people are gone now.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:13.630
So tomorrow night, you'll see
the three people in the center

00:04:13.630 --> 00:04:14.760
for the Democratic Debate.

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:17.040
How many of you are going
to spend Saturday evening

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:19.220
watching the Democratic Debate?

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:20.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:21.690
OK.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:22.810
Fair enough.

00:04:22.810 --> 00:04:24.130
And you guys are lucky.

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:25.890
You don't have to
wait until 9:00.

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:27.080
I'm in the New York area.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:30.260
I have to wait until
9:00 PM to watch that.

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:32.510
But you can watch it,
of course, any time,

00:04:32.510 --> 00:04:34.150
because they'll
record it and you'll

00:04:34.150 --> 00:04:36.380
be able to watch it on YouTube.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:39.100
So the three in the
middle will be there.

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:43.430
And then, the
Republicans, a few of them

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:46.110
are now gone, or on
different stages,

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:49.740
and so, yeah,
things have changed,

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:51.040
and they're changing rapidly.

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:52.170
It's a moving target.

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:54.580
And it's something that I
have to constantly figure

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:57.175
out and work on,
because, again, there

00:04:57.175 --> 00:04:59.890
have been so many debates
and so many changes

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:02.210
that it's been
difficult to keep up.

00:05:02.210 --> 00:05:03.930
I couldn't even update
from the other day

00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:05.610
because I was so busy.

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:10.250
But there was a debate on
Tuesday, I think it was.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:12.610
So it doesn't matter
whether you want

00:05:12.610 --> 00:05:14.440
to move to Pennsylvania
Avenue, you

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:16.640
want to move into 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue,

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:18.770
or you want to move
up in Silicon Valley.

00:05:18.770 --> 00:05:23.940
The better communicator, or the
best communicator, will win.

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:28.360
I want to make it very clear--
you do not have to be perfect.

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:30.400
You do not have to be great.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:33.580
You just have to be better
than the competition.

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:34.560
It's like the Olympics.

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:36.880
You just have to win by
a fraction of a point.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:39.780
And that is the way it
is for these candidates,

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:41.990
and for you, as well.

00:05:41.990 --> 00:05:47.660
So there are five components
to candidate communications

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:48.960
success.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:51.780
Let's list five components.

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:54.400
The first is presentation
skills and public speaking.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:55.470
This is the biggest one.

00:05:55.470 --> 00:05:56.640
It's the most important one.

00:05:56.640 --> 00:05:59.460
It's the way that we get to
know them a little better,

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:03.530
or they try to get us to
know them a little better.

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:06.690
And we'll spend most of the
time on the presentation skills

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:09.100
and public speaking today.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:10.950
The second one is content.

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:11.660
Message.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:14.620
So we're going to spend
some time on their slogans,

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:17.250
and what they use
for their slogans.

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:19.300
But generally, it's
their messaging.

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:21.270
What exactly are they saying?

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:24.390
And then, beyond the
message itself, discipline.

00:06:24.390 --> 00:06:27.180
How often do they
repeat the message?

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:29.070
Do they stick with
the same message?

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:31.446
Are they testing some new
versions and variations

00:06:31.446 --> 00:06:32.070
of the message?

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:36.230
And how do they put those--
the sloganeering is great,

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:38.770
I find it fascinating,
because if you put together

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:41.774
slogans in a certain way, they
should roll off your tongue

00:06:41.774 --> 00:06:43.190
and they should
be very memorable,

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:47.640
and they should have some
kind of an emotional impact.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.180
The third issue is the
personal narrative.

00:06:52.180 --> 00:06:53.840
This is the story
of who they are,

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:58.660
how they come to be who they
are, and how they're formed.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:01.800
And this is another
way that we end up

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:06.190
feeling like he or she
gets me, or he or she

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:08.140
doesn't get me at all.

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:11.570
And then there are two final
communication components

00:07:11.570 --> 00:07:14.590
that we're not going to have
time to talk about here today.

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:19.000
And the fourth one is
interpersonal communication,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.710
one-on-one communication,
or one-on-small-groups,

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:23.740
that's very important
in business,

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:27.740
hugely important in business,
but we don't have time to go

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:29.470
into that in any detail today.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:31.530
One of the things
that you should know

00:07:31.530 --> 00:07:33.650
is that, as the
race narrows down,

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:37.890
and the press pool
isn't so spread out,

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:41.620
spread so thin, that they
will be following the two

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:43.150
eventual nominees.

00:07:43.150 --> 00:07:46.310
And what will happen
is, these nominees

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:49.030
will be photographed in the
diners, in the boutiques,

00:07:49.030 --> 00:07:53.940
in the shops, in the businesses,
the manufacturing businesses.

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:56.610
Maybe they'll come to Google,
but only to get money.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:57.300
Right?

00:07:57.300 --> 00:07:59.383
Because they only come to
New York and Connecticut

00:07:59.383 --> 00:08:00.590
to get money.

00:08:00.590 --> 00:08:01.950
We never see them, either.

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:05.730
But so they come,
they'll be photographed,

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:11.100
and reporters will report on
how they interact, one-on-one,

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:13.239
with the "regular folks," OK?

00:08:13.239 --> 00:08:14.780
That's what they
think of, and that's

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:17.570
how they qualify it--
the regular folks.

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:21.060
And then the final communication
component is the spouse.

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:23.600
Not going to talk about
that at all today.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:26.720
[LAUGHTER] Very hard to talk
about for obvious reasons.

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.440
But we do have some interesting
spousal possibilities

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:38.549
for the potential First
Spouse this time, right?

00:08:38.549 --> 00:08:42.110
So let's start with the public
speaking and presentation.

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:47.730
And I want to play
a video or two.

