00:15:57.460 --> 00:16:01.530
Bernie Sanders has this
hand gesture that he uses.

00:16:01.530 --> 00:16:07.210
When he talks, he punctuate
each syllable of each word.

00:16:07.210 --> 00:16:09.710
And uses his right hand, and
sometimes he gets his left hand

00:16:09.710 --> 00:16:11.230
into the act.

00:16:11.230 --> 00:16:15.980
But he punctuates each
syllable of each word.

00:16:15.980 --> 00:16:18.220
And the problem that
he's had with that

00:16:18.220 --> 00:16:20.750
is that when you
are speaking, you're

00:16:20.750 --> 00:16:23.560
speaking in a faster
manner, your syllables

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:26.010
are moving more quickly
off your tongue,

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:28.310
than your hand can move.

00:16:28.310 --> 00:16:30.230
So you're late with your hands.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:31.250
OK?

00:16:31.250 --> 00:16:32.750
And we'll see that
in just a second.

00:16:32.750 --> 00:16:36.980
Just slightly late, and I'm
exaggerating, but you're late.

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:40.120
And it's a bit of a
distraction because of that.

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:42.400
So we're going to take a
look at that in a minute.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:44.660
But let's talk a little
bit about gestures

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:47.020
and why they're so important.

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:51.000
The research shows that
gestures help us think.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.210
They help us think.

00:16:53.210 --> 00:16:54.860
I don't know about
any of you, but when

00:16:54.860 --> 00:16:56.810
you get to a certain
age, like I am,

00:16:56.810 --> 00:16:58.890
you're looking for
words sometimes.

00:16:58.890 --> 00:17:00.250
Trying to find words.

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:02.620
Sometimes I'm struggling,
trying to find a word,

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.380
and I'm waving my
hand around up here

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:09.569
as if I can pluck it out of the
air and put it into my brain.

00:17:09.569 --> 00:17:10.849
And many of us do that.

00:17:10.849 --> 00:17:11.829
We use our hands.

00:17:11.829 --> 00:17:14.890
And as we express
ourselves, we use our hands.

00:17:14.890 --> 00:17:17.589
And if you watch
what people do, even

00:17:17.589 --> 00:17:20.780
in interpersonal communication,
you are using their hands.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:22.810
If there's a culture
that does not

00:17:22.810 --> 00:17:27.640
use its hands to
accompany the spoken word,

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:29.390
it hasn't been discovered yet.

00:17:29.390 --> 00:17:31.030
Hasn't been discovered yet.

00:17:31.030 --> 00:17:34.080
And one of the ways they
know that hand gestures are

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:37.820
so important is that blind
people gesture, and deaf people

00:17:37.820 --> 00:17:40.220
gesture in addition to signing.

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:42.330
So gestures are
hugely important.

00:17:42.330 --> 00:17:43.790
So not only do
they help us think,

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:46.640
but they help
everyone else learn.

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:48.480
Nonverbal communication,
the way you look,

00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:51.650
sound, move, and travel,
gives meaning to your words.

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:53.160
It makes you believable.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:54.875
Give you a quick example.

00:17:54.875 --> 00:17:59.090
If I stood here like this,
and I said, I'm Ruth Sherman,

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:05.160
