00:24:02.180 --> 00:24:04.790
we still speak far more
than we do any of that.

00:24:04.790 --> 00:24:05.799
Far more.

00:24:05.799 --> 00:24:07.590
And we don't even
realize it, because we're

00:24:07.590 --> 00:24:10.320
sitting at our computers,
typing away all the time.

00:24:10.320 --> 00:24:12.660
But the fact is that
we do it far more,

00:24:12.660 --> 00:24:15.570
and it's much more efficient.

00:24:15.570 --> 00:24:17.367
So the speaking voice.

00:24:17.367 --> 00:24:18.700
Talked about the speaking voice.

00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:19.370
I mentioned it.

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:21.620
It's in a class by
itself because it

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:23.470
has several components.

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:26.000
Volume, which we just
talked about with Sanders.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:31.010
It has a tone,
intonation, expression, so

00:24:31.010 --> 00:24:34.680
the way we use pitch, highs
and lows, to express our voice

00:24:34.680 --> 00:24:36.130
and all of the range in between.

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:40.350
By the way, every language
has its own music.

00:24:40.350 --> 00:24:42.820
Has its own linguistic music.

00:24:42.820 --> 00:24:47.340
So that's why, when we
speak a foreign language,

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:48.990
our native accent is there.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:52.970
Because we're using our
music from our native tongue

00:24:52.970 --> 00:24:56.660
to speak the other language,
the foreign language.

00:24:56.660 --> 00:24:59.060
But the other things
that is has, of course,

00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:02.780
is the accent and dialect, and
then, as I mentioned, volume,

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:04.590
tone, expression, et cetera.

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:05.220
And rate.

00:25:05.220 --> 00:25:06.250
And pace.

00:25:06.250 --> 00:25:09.470
So let's listen
to two candidates,

00:25:09.470 --> 00:25:14.480
back to back-- Jeb Bush and
Martin O'Malley, both of whom,

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:17.900
I think, have beautiful
speaking voices.

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:19.231
Let's take a quick listen.

00:25:19.231 --> 00:25:19.730
Yeah.

00:25:19.730 --> 00:25:22.607
AUDIENCE: Question, just before
you move on from Sanders,

00:25:22.607 --> 00:25:25.190
why isn't he-- you know, these
campaigns cost tens or hundreds

00:25:25.190 --> 00:25:28.030
of millions of dollars, why, and
it's pretty clear to everybody,

00:25:28.030 --> 00:25:30.457
why hasn't he
actually addressed it?

00:25:30.457 --> 00:25:32.290
RUTH SHERMAN: Your guess
is as good as mine.

00:25:32.290 --> 00:25:34.250
I don't have inside information.

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:34.750
Sadly.

00:25:34.750 --> 00:25:36.840
AUDIENCE: Do you think he
knows that this hurting him?

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:38.790
RUTH SHERMAN: I'm sure
somebody's telling him.

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:40.950
I would guess
somebody's telling him.

00:25:40.950 --> 00:25:44.550
But either he's not
listening, or he doesn't care,

00:25:44.550 --> 00:25:48.190
or he thinks that it will impact
his quote unquote authenticity.

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:50.430
And, you know.

00:25:50.430 --> 00:25:51.490
So I don't know.

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:53.319
But that's the only
thing I can think of.

00:25:53.319 --> 00:25:54.860
That's the only
thing I can think of.

00:25:54.860 --> 00:26:01.974
Let's take a quick look, or
listen, to O'Malley and Bush.

00:26:01.974 --> 00:26:03.765
And I'll try to push
the right button here.

00:26:03.765 --> 00:26:03.920
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:04.795
-To a certain extent.

00:26:04.795 --> 00:26:06.950
I always knew this
was going to be hard.

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:08.904
I never felt like I
was a front-runner,

00:26:08.904 --> 00:26:10.070
because we hadn't earned it.

00:26:10.070 --> 00:26:13.070
We haven't-- Just starting
out on the journey,

00:26:13.070 --> 00:26:14.310
you've got to go earn it.

00:26:14.310 --> 00:26:16.190
I've got to get better
at debating, I guess,

00:26:16.190 --> 00:26:16.880
or performing.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:17.871
Whatever that's called.

00:26:17.871 --> 00:26:18.370
And I will.

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:19.550
I'm a grinder.

00:26:19.550 --> 00:26:20.680
I'm very competitive.

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:21.480
And so I feel good
about where we are.

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:22.440
-What is that?

00:26:22.440 --> 00:26:24.310
You keep saying, I'm a grinder.

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:25.310
What does that mean?

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:28.020
-That means, I described
it as I eat nails

00:26:28.020 --> 00:26:29.620
before I have breakfast.

00:26:29.620 --> 00:26:30.400
I'm focused.

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:32.470
I'm competitive.

00:26:32.470 --> 00:26:34.555
I've set high
expectations on myself.

00:26:34.555 --> 00:26:35.930
I knew this was
going to be hard.

00:26:35.930 --> 00:26:36.660
- --New leadership.

00:26:36.660 --> 00:26:38.000
You're ready to challenge
her, aren't you?

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:39.583
-Well, I think that
our country always

00:26:39.583 --> 00:26:42.910
benefits from new leadership
and new perspectives.

00:26:42.910 --> 00:26:44.560
And let's be honest here.

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:46.580
The Presidency of
the United States

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:50.480
is not some crown to be
passed between two families.

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:53.260
It is an awesome
and sacred trust

00:26:53.260 --> 00:26:56.297
to be earned and exercised on
behalf of the American people.

00:26:56.297 --> 00:26:57.880
-Those two families,
Bush and Clinton?

00:26:57.880 --> 00:27:02.580
-Well, right now, George,
you know, any two families.

00:27:02.580 --> 00:27:03.490
But look.

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:05.960
In order for us to
make an economy again,

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:08.190
where people can work
hard and get ahead,

00:27:08.190 --> 00:27:10.850
we need a president
who is on our side.

00:27:10.850 --> 00:27:12.270
A president who's
willing to take

00:27:12.270 --> 00:27:14.450
on powerful, wealthy,
special interests,

00:27:14.450 --> 00:27:17.340
in order to restore that
sort of American economy

00:27:17.340 --> 00:27:19.665
where, wherever you start
on the earning spectrum,

00:27:19.665 --> 00:27:21.373
you can get ahead
through your hard work.

00:27:21.373 --> 00:27:21.956
[END PLAYBACK]

00:27:21.956 --> 00:27:24.770
RUTH SHERMAN: So if we
listen to O'Malley and Bush,

00:27:24.770 --> 00:27:26.064
their voices are very pleasing.

00:27:26.064 --> 00:27:28.480
I think it was interesting
when Bush said, "I'm a grinder.

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:29.360
I'm a grinder."

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:30.901
It's like, well,
what does that mean?

00:27:30.901 --> 00:27:33.310
And you don't look like
a grinder right now.

00:27:33.310 --> 00:27:34.540
So.

00:27:34.540 --> 00:27:37.530
He could've-- when she asked
him what a grinder was,

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:40.610
we could have learned what
that was if he expressed it

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:42.410
a certain way.

00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:44.090
But O'Malley and
Bush are pretty good.

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:47.000
Now the other thing
that happens--

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.140
I don't have the recordings
of the women's voices,

00:27:49.140 --> 00:27:51.320
except you heard
Carly Fiorina before.

00:27:51.320 --> 00:27:53.720
The women's voices, Hillary
Clinton and Carly Fiorina,

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:54.230
they're OK.

00:27:54.230 --> 00:27:56.240
They're good enough voices.

00:27:56.240 --> 00:28:00.070
They're not beautiful women's
voices, like-- oh, gosh.

00:28:00.070 --> 00:28:03.920
One of the great women's voices
right now that you could listen

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:05.130
to would be Diane Sawyer.

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:10.100
Probably the best public voice
that you can hear from a woman.

00:28:10.100 --> 00:28:13.675
Beautifully articulated and well
done, and very well-trained,

00:28:13.675 --> 00:28:14.660
of course.

00:28:14.660 --> 00:28:16.000
But their voices are good.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:17.160
They're good enough.

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:21.990
And they've learned
how to create and use

00:28:21.990 --> 00:28:24.360
their leadership voices.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:26.470
One of the things that
you don't hear from them,

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:30.185
that we hear a lot, I
hear a lot among clients,

00:28:30.185 --> 00:28:32.310
and you may hear it a lot,
but I want you to become

00:28:32.310 --> 00:28:34.355
more aware of this, is uptalk.

00:28:34.355 --> 00:28:36.100
Uptalk sounds like this.

00:28:36.100 --> 00:28:37.721
Everything sounds
like a question.

00:28:37.721 --> 00:28:38.220
All right?

00:28:38.220 --> 00:28:39.885
And I'm being very
nasal right now,

00:28:39.885 --> 00:28:41.220
and I'm trying to imitate it.

00:28:41.220 --> 00:28:43.950
And I'm a girl, I'm a
woman, so this is the way

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.930
it sounds when women do it.

00:28:46.930 --> 00:28:47.860
Men do it, too.

00:28:47.860 --> 00:28:51.130
Women get nailed
for more, sadly.

00:28:51.130 --> 00:28:52.230
But that is the way it is.

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:53.460
So let me play this for you.

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:57.410
You'll hear another habit,
which is called vocal fry.

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:03.444
Which I can't do
as well as she can.

00:29:03.444 --> 00:29:04.110
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:06.460
-America's young
women are running out

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:10.270
of oxygen. What else could
explain why so many of them

00:29:10.270 --> 00:29:12.180
sound like this.

00:29:12.180 --> 00:29:13.930
-So cute.

00:29:13.930 --> 00:29:15.186
So cute.

00:29:15.186 --> 00:29:16.102
-Hi.

00:29:16.102 --> 00:29:16.700
Hi.

00:29:16.700 --> 00:29:17.200
Hi.

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:20.540
-Just kind of like my, you
know, motto, you know, motto.

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:22.220
-Kim and Khloe
just don't get it.

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:22.720
Get it.

00:29:22.720 --> 00:29:23.220
Get it.

00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:24.472
[END PLAYBACK]

00:29:24.472 --> 00:29:27.385
RUTH SHERMAN:
[LAUGHS] So vocal fry.

00:29:27.385 --> 00:29:28.840
Well, actually,
that's when you--

00:29:28.840 --> 00:29:31.790
you know that the air is
just coming out so slowly.

00:29:31.790 --> 00:29:35.410
You're not pushing the air over
your vocal cords fast enough.

00:29:35.410 --> 00:29:36.520
That's what it is.

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:40.240
I remember when George W. Bush--
now, that's interesting, too.

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:42.210
That's an interesting
juxtaposition.

00:29:42.210 --> 00:29:45.350
George W. Bush's
voice was awful.

00:29:45.350 --> 00:29:46.100
Awful.

00:29:46.100 --> 00:29:46.810
Awful.

00:29:46.810 --> 00:29:47.741
Awful.

00:29:47.741 --> 00:29:48.240
All right?

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:50.160
So you would think
brothers sound alike.

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:51.150
They don't.

00:29:51.150 --> 00:29:51.980
They don't.

00:29:51.980 --> 00:29:56.110
You know, my sisters and I
sound alike, but, I don't know.

00:29:56.110 --> 00:29:59.060
They lost that gene somewhere.

00:29:59.060 --> 00:29:59.560
OK.

00:29:59.560 --> 00:30:00.090
So.

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:00.590
Voice.

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:01.470
Very important.

00:30:01.470 --> 00:30:02.160
Be assertive.

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:03.091
Use your voice.

00:30:03.091 --> 00:30:04.590
You know, if your
voice is too high,

00:30:04.590 --> 00:30:06.980
lower it a little
bit, for women.

00:30:06.980 --> 00:30:10.510
Men, make sure you push that
air over your vocal cords,

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:12.210
so you don't get vocal fry.

00:30:12.210 --> 00:30:13.027
All right?

00:30:13.027 --> 00:30:15.610
What I was going to say a moment
ago was, when George W. Bush,

00:30:15.610 --> 00:30:17.510
I remember, entertaining
the thought, early

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:21.010
in his Presidency, of
having Henry Kissinger do

00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:22.566
some kind of work.

00:30:22.566 --> 00:30:24.940
And I thought, oh my god, if
I have to listen-- You know,

00:30:24.940 --> 00:30:26.220
I've been around a long time.

00:30:26.220 --> 00:30:29.250
I remember when Kissinger
was on TV all the time.

00:30:29.250 --> 00:30:31.790
And I thought, if I have to
listen to that every night

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:33.020
on the news, kill myself.

00:30:33.020 --> 00:30:33.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:34.670
Kill myself.

00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:35.950
Only because of his voice.

00:30:35.950 --> 00:30:38.580
[LAUGHS] All right.

00:30:38.580 --> 00:30:41.600
The other nonverbal
code of communication

00:30:41.600 --> 00:30:45.270
we can talk about briefly
today is dress and adornment.

00:30:45.270 --> 00:30:47.250
Dress and adornment.

00:30:47.250 --> 00:30:49.210
Everything you
weren't born wearing.

00:30:49.210 --> 00:30:52.160
All the choices that we make.

00:30:52.160 --> 00:30:54.640
All the choices we
make, from the way

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:58.280
we comb our hair, haircuts,
everything, the whole thing.

00:30:58.280 --> 00:30:59.380
Dress and adornment.

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:03.120
There's a uniform,
obviously, that politicians

00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:05.380
have to wear if they're
on the debates stages,

00:31:05.380 --> 00:31:07.677
or in a formal setting.

00:31:07.677 --> 00:31:09.510
The men are going to
be wearing a dark suit,

00:31:09.510 --> 00:31:13.170
a light-colored shirt,
and a red or blue-ish tie.

00:31:13.170 --> 00:31:13.880
That's it.

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:14.380
All right?

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:17.210
The women have more choices,
and it's more fraught.

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:17.960
It's more fraught.

00:31:17.960 --> 00:31:20.040
I remember somebody
asking me why

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:21.910
Hillary Clinton
wore that blue suit

00:31:21.910 --> 00:31:23.380
on the first Democratic debate.

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:26.950
I said I didn't think she
wanted to stand out as much.

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:29.150
She didn't want to
be-- Women are always

00:31:29.150 --> 00:31:33.157
going to be approached
or criticized, certainly,

00:31:33.157 --> 00:31:35.240
but there's always going
to be comments about what

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:36.920
it is that they wear.

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:38.960
So I think she wanted
to lessen that.

00:31:38.960 --> 00:31:41.310
And I think it worked for her.

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:42.540
So dress and adornment.

00:31:42.540 --> 00:31:44.107
You know, I thought
a lot about what

00:31:44.107 --> 00:31:45.940
I was going to wear to
here, because I'm not

00:31:45.940 --> 00:31:47.520
going to wear this to a bank.

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:51.240
I'm not wearing this outfit
to J. P. Morgan when I go

00:31:51.240 --> 00:31:52.520
and I talk to them.

00:31:52.520 --> 00:31:55.870
I wore a suit yesterday
at Accenture in San Jose,

00:31:55.870 --> 00:31:57.720
because I was speaking
to a group there.

00:31:57.720 --> 00:31:58.730
It was different.

00:31:58.730 --> 00:32:02.620
I knew, and I asked [? Doma, ?]
what's the dress code?

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:03.690
And she told me informal.

00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:04.680
And I knew that.

00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:05.670
I knew it was informal.

00:32:05.670 --> 00:32:07.420
But I wanted to
confirm it, because I

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:08.890
hadn't been here before.

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:11.220
So I thought, OK, well, what
can I wear that's informal

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:12.139
but that's still me?

00:32:12.139 --> 00:32:14.180
You know, still it's got
a little bit of an edge,

00:32:14.180 --> 00:32:15.550
little bit stylish,
because I'm not

00:32:15.550 --> 00:32:17.424
going to come in here
in jeans and a T-shirt,

00:32:17.424 --> 00:32:19.520
or even khakis and
a button-down shirt.

00:32:19.520 --> 00:32:21.030
That's not me.

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:24.880
So I was glad to be able to
find something that I had,

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:27.100
that I thought would work.

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:29.320
So I'll leave that up to you.

00:32:29.320 --> 00:32:31.981
You can let me know whether
you think it works or not.

00:32:31.981 --> 00:32:32.480
But--

00:32:32.480 --> 00:32:33.120
AUDIENCE: It's working.

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:34.244
RUTH SHERMAN: It's working?

00:32:34.244 --> 00:32:36.050
Thank you. [LAUGHS] Thank you.

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:37.390
I'm glad about that.

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:40.100
But the whole idea
that we think,

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:45.610
oh, we get up in the morning, in
Silicon Valley, that you think,

00:32:45.610 --> 00:32:48.090
oh gosh, I don't have to
worry about any of that stuff,

00:32:48.090 --> 00:32:49.990
because what you're
communicating,

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:52.390
of course, is this
is not important.

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:54.140
This isn't important.

00:32:54.140 --> 00:32:55.780
This is important.

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:57.450
But guess what?

00:32:57.450 --> 00:33:02.760
A long time ago, somebody
chose this uniform for you.

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:04.120
Somebody chose it.

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:07.420
And it, in fact,
communicates something.

00:33:07.420 --> 00:33:11.050
You cannot get away from
communicating, regardless,

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:13.615
whether you think you are,
or you think you aren't.

00:33:19.420 --> 00:33:22.647
One more thing about
presentation skills

00:33:22.647 --> 00:33:23.480
and public speaking.

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:27.640
In order to get good at it,
you have got to practice.

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:30.550
You've got to practice, and
you have to say it out loud.

00:33:30.550 --> 00:33:33.000
In your head does not count.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.930
We're all very eloquent
in our own heads.

00:33:35.930 --> 00:33:36.540
We are.

00:33:36.540 --> 00:33:39.000
We imagine ourselves getting
up on a stage or platform,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.070
or conducting that meeting,
and being wonderful.

00:33:42.070 --> 00:33:44.010
It doesn't work that way.

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:46.300
If you practice, say
it out loud a lot,

00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:48.660
and then you get
to the other side,

00:33:48.660 --> 00:33:50.690
where you can get up
there, and maybe you're

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:51.972
nervous to begin with.

00:33:51.972 --> 00:33:54.180
And by the way, I don't call
it stage fright anymore.

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:55.325
I just saw this.

00:33:55.325 --> 00:33:57.421
Call it stage appreciation.

00:33:57.421 --> 00:33:57.920
OK?

00:33:57.920 --> 00:33:58.920
Think about it that way.

00:33:58.920 --> 00:34:01.245
It's a re-frame of that feeling.

