RUTH SHERMAN: You know?

00:47:53.085 --> 00:47:56.080
I mean, he's interesting.

00:47:56.080 --> 00:47:58.370
He's an interesting guy.

00:47:58.370 --> 00:47:59.220
OK.

00:47:59.220 --> 00:48:00.950
Let's talk about the
personal narrative.

00:48:00.950 --> 00:48:01.520
The story.

00:48:01.520 --> 00:48:03.430
The core.

00:48:03.430 --> 00:48:08.080
The hero journey that each
person in the world takes.

00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:11.200
Some people have a better
hero-journey story than others.

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:15.030
Like Barack Obama had a
fantastic hero-journey story.

00:48:15.030 --> 00:48:18.240
But what happens if you've
been raised either wealthy,

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:20.530
or middle class, you don't
have that much hardship,

00:48:20.530 --> 00:48:23.240
you haven't had to overcome
the same kinds of things

00:48:23.240 --> 00:48:27.200
that somebody like
Obama had to overcome.

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:29.930
Or like Ben Carson now,
who's talking about what

00:48:29.930 --> 00:48:32.520
he's had to overcome.

00:48:32.520 --> 00:48:34.610
So what do you do about that?

00:48:34.610 --> 00:48:36.980
Well, it's another way
that we get to know people.

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:39.900
One of the things that
I think is interesting,

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:43.400
as we look at
Hillary Clinton, she

00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:46.250
was raised in a
middle-class family.

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:48.650
Her father was a businessman.

00:48:48.650 --> 00:48:50.660
Her mother, she talks
about her mother

00:48:50.660 --> 00:48:52.320
having been thrown
out of the house,

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:55.472
or having to leave
home at the age of 14

00:48:55.472 --> 00:48:56.430
and make it on her own.

00:48:56.430 --> 00:48:58.513
So she's talking about
that, but that hasn't quite

00:48:58.513 --> 00:49:00.750
connected with people yet.

00:49:00.750 --> 00:49:01.840
It hasn't quite connected.

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:03.440
I don't know that it will.

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:05.580
I think that there's
certain times when you just

00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:06.930
have to run on your resume.

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:09.830
And I think that's what she
will end up doing, in terms

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:12.170
of telling her story,
in how she came up,

00:49:12.170 --> 00:49:15.670
and how she came up through
the women's movement,

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:17.665
and became a professional
lawyer, and a partner

00:49:17.665 --> 00:49:24.780
in a firm, and all of her work
for girls and women, et cetera.

00:49:24.780 --> 00:49:29.830
And her resume is very
lengthy and quite impressive.

00:49:29.830 --> 00:49:33.575
Carly Fiorina, from
secretary to CEO.

00:49:33.575 --> 00:49:35.370
A little alliteration there.

00:49:35.370 --> 00:49:37.340
And we can make fun
of her, and think,

00:49:37.340 --> 00:49:39.362
like, she also was raised
in the middle class

00:49:39.362 --> 00:49:40.570
or upper middle class family.

00:49:40.570 --> 00:49:43.400
I don't think she had
much hardship growing up.

00:49:43.400 --> 00:49:45.750
But the idea that
she was a secretary.

00:49:45.750 --> 00:49:48.320
You know, she and I
are about the same age.

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:52.570
She-- When I started
working, I was a receptionist

00:49:52.570 --> 00:49:54.470
in an accounting
firm in New York.

00:49:54.470 --> 00:49:55.612
I couldn't get a job.

00:49:55.612 --> 00:49:56.570
I wasn't an accountant.

00:49:56.570 --> 00:49:58.750
But I wouldn't have been
able to get a job like you,

00:49:58.750 --> 00:50:01.450
like all of the women now,
who graduate college and get

00:50:01.450 --> 00:50:03.800
real jobs, real
professional jobs.

00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:05.880
It's an amazing transformation.

00:50:05.880 --> 00:50:08.142
I sometimes think the
women's movement is stalled,

00:50:08.142 --> 00:50:10.100
but then I come to places
like this, in Google,

00:50:10.100 --> 00:50:12.250
and Accenture yesterday,
and I think, thank

00:50:12.250 --> 00:50:16.100
god, it hasn't stalled.

00:50:16.100 --> 00:50:17.370
It is much better.

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:18.590
It feels glacial.

00:50:18.590 --> 00:50:21.630
But that's going to be
Carly Fiorina's frame.

00:50:21.630 --> 00:50:24.470
Donald Trump has a frame story.

00:50:24.470 --> 00:50:27.620
Donald Trump has a problem
talking about his life.

00:50:27.620 --> 00:50:30.000
He came from a wealthy family.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:31.500
His father was a developer.

00:50:31.500 --> 00:50:34.290
He's mentioned one
thing about his--

00:50:34.290 --> 00:50:39.980
had a brother who died
unexpectedly, or too young,

00:50:39.980 --> 00:50:41.260
I think from alcoholism.

00:50:41.260 --> 00:50:42.094
I think that was it.

00:50:42.094 --> 00:50:43.510
But he doesn't
talk about it much,

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:45.160
so we don't really
know much about him.

00:50:45.160 --> 00:50:47.700
But we don't really care,
because Donald Trump isn't

00:50:47.700 --> 00:50:50.200
expected to be introspective.

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:51.252
So it's consistent.

00:50:51.252 --> 00:50:51.960
It's interesting.

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:53.990
It's consistent with his brand.

00:50:53.990 --> 00:50:59.260
Bernie Sanders has the story
of he's been in politics now

00:50:59.260 --> 00:51:02.010
for 25 or 30 years,
I think about, yeah,

00:51:02.010 --> 00:51:04.740
about 25 or 30 years,
so he can't go back

00:51:04.740 --> 00:51:07.140
and say, well I'm
sort of an outsider.

00:51:07.140 --> 00:51:08.280
He's not.

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:08.970
But what is it?

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:11.410
He comes from a small state.

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:14.350
What is it that Bernie Sanders
can bring to the table?

00:51:14.350 --> 00:51:16.500
He's a father, I think,
of four children,

00:51:16.500 --> 00:51:18.130
a grandfather of seven.

00:51:18.130 --> 00:51:20.020
He talks about that
a lot, so that people

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:22.640
can relate to him in that way.

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:25.250
Ben Carson, we know his
story, and now they're

00:51:25.250 --> 00:51:26.670
starting to pick
on him about it.

00:51:26.670 --> 00:51:29.170
I don't know whether any of its
true, whether it's not true.

00:51:29.170 --> 00:51:30.190
I don't have any idea.

00:51:30.190 --> 00:51:33.980
But it's compelling stuff,
if you think about it.

00:51:33.980 --> 00:51:35.770
One of the most
interesting things,

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:39.066
as I was following
politics in the-- I

00:51:39.066 --> 00:51:44.236
remember when George Bush was
running against John Kerry.

00:51:44.236 --> 00:51:47.280
Now George Bush is from
one of the first families

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:48.650
of American politics.

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:49.910
The Bush family.

00:51:49.910 --> 00:51:51.510
Been in politics.

00:51:51.510 --> 00:51:52.490
Wealthy New Englanders.

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:55.920
And then in Texas, oil
business, for decades.

00:51:58.810 --> 00:52:01.290
So George Bush was running
against John Kerry.

00:52:01.290 --> 00:52:04.570
John Kerry got the reputation
as being the patrician.

00:52:04.570 --> 00:52:07.970
George Bush, his story
was, his narrative

00:52:07.970 --> 00:52:10.800
was that he would be
filmed on his ranch,

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:14.080
clearing brush in his
flannel shirt and his jeans,

00:52:14.080 --> 00:52:16.900
and his cowboy boots
and his cowboy hat,

00:52:16.900 --> 00:52:21.630
and his dogs in tow, and in
his dusty pickup truck, right?

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:22.300
Clearing brush.

00:52:22.300 --> 00:52:25.070
That's what he was always
doing on his weekends.

00:52:25.070 --> 00:52:28.590
John Kerry was
windsurfing off Nantucket.

00:52:28.590 --> 00:52:31.690
You don't do that if you
want to run for President,

00:52:31.690 --> 00:52:34.140
and you want people to think
that you're not the patrician

00:52:34.140 --> 00:52:34.770
one.

00:52:34.770 --> 00:52:37.640
So their personal narrative
is going to be very important.

00:52:37.640 --> 00:52:38.980
They're going to flesh this out.

00:52:38.980 --> 00:52:42.430
It's going to come up,
and we're going to see it.

00:52:42.430 --> 00:52:47.070
For you, in business, you
don't want to get too personal.

00:52:47.070 --> 00:52:49.650
Not in a large group.

00:52:49.650 --> 00:52:51.280
Certainly not.

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:53.530
With your colleagues, close
colleagues, and people

00:52:53.530 --> 00:52:55.160
you have good
relationships with, yes.

00:52:55.160 --> 00:52:57.060
You can tell them some
of your struggles.

00:52:57.060 --> 00:53:01.080
But in business,
leaders that I work with

00:53:01.080 --> 00:53:03.109
are always advised
to find something

00:53:03.109 --> 00:53:05.150
that they can talk about
where it didn't work out

00:53:05.150 --> 00:53:06.410
so well for them.

00:53:06.410 --> 00:53:09.550
Where they failed, and how they
struggled with that failure,

00:53:09.550 --> 00:53:12.230
and how they fixed
it and came back.

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:14.510
Whether it was they
were fired, or they

00:53:14.510 --> 00:53:18.220
failed on a big project, or
something of that nature,

00:53:18.220 --> 00:53:20.460
that makes them seem more human.

00:53:20.460 --> 00:53:22.620
People will connect
with you if they

00:53:22.620 --> 00:53:25.230
think, like I said at the
outset, when I was introducing

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:28.600
this, if they think that you
are a human being who can relate

00:53:28.600 --> 00:53:31.420
to them, who gets
them, who knows

00:53:31.420 --> 00:53:35.810
what the cost of an evening
out for dinner would be.

00:53:35.810 --> 00:53:41.240
Who knows what the cost of a
roll of toilet paper would be.

00:53:41.240 --> 00:53:44.160
So I want to close
by telling you

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:52.880
that it doesn't matter whether
you think you are good at this,

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:54.180
or you think you're not.

00:53:54.180 --> 00:53:55.880
These are skills
that can be learned.

00:53:55.880 --> 00:53:57.550
This is not inborn.

00:53:57.550 --> 00:53:59.940
These are concrete skills
that can be learned.

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:03.790
I would imagine that Google
has all kinds of workshops.

00:54:03.790 --> 00:54:07.080
If you need to go
a little further,

00:54:07.080 --> 00:54:09.850
there's the National
Speakers Association.

00:54:09.850 --> 00:54:11.500
And they have a San
Francisco chapter.

00:54:11.500 --> 00:54:13.870
If you need to go further,
but closer to home,

00:54:13.870 --> 00:54:15.940
look for your
Toastmasters chapter,

00:54:15.940 --> 00:54:18.320
or somebody start
one here at Google,

00:54:18.320 --> 00:54:20.270
if you don't already have one.

00:54:20.270 --> 00:54:20.910
You have one.

00:54:20.910 --> 00:54:21.410
Yeah.

00:54:21.410 --> 00:54:22.970
You have probably
several, right?

00:54:22.970 --> 00:54:24.270
Several chapters?

00:54:24.270 --> 00:54:24.780
Yeah?

00:54:24.780 --> 00:54:25.280
OK.

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:26.010
Not a surprise.

00:54:26.010 --> 00:54:26.510
Go!

00:54:26.510 --> 00:54:27.390
Do this stuff.

00:54:27.390 --> 00:54:28.730
Get better at this.

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:30.650
Get some objective feedback.

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:33.620
Because it will
advance your career.

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:35.120
Because here's the
truth-- no matter

00:54:35.120 --> 00:54:39.210
how much experience you
have, how long you've

00:54:39.210 --> 00:54:42.650
been in business, how
much you love what you do,

00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:46.560
and critically,
how smart you are,

00:54:46.560 --> 00:54:49.809
if you don't have a
commanding presence, if you

00:54:49.809 --> 00:54:52.350
don't know how to communicate,
you will continue to struggle.

00:54:52.350 --> 00:54:57.310
You'll continue to be
underpaid and under-recognized.

00:54:57.310 --> 00:54:59.540
And you'll continue
to labor to get

00:54:59.540 --> 00:55:04.380
the people to find you, and help
you, and promote you, and give

00:55:04.380 --> 00:55:07.340
you the bonuses and the
recognition you deserve.

00:55:07.340 --> 00:55:12.990
These are the skills that cure
all those ills more quickly

00:55:12.990 --> 00:55:13.840
than anything else.

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:17.220
A colleague of mine calls
it a shortcut to sales.

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:20.810
There are no shortcuts in life,
except communication and public

00:55:20.810 --> 00:55:22.330
speaking.

00:55:22.330 --> 00:55:23.310
Thank you very much.

00:55:23.310 --> 00:55:27.830
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:27.830 --> 00:55:29.920
What questions do you have?

00:55:29.920 --> 00:55:33.340
AUDIENCE: So I remember Barack
