00:55:33.340 --> 00:55:35.630
having a sense of he was
really speaking to me,

00:55:35.630 --> 00:55:38.130
or he really has a message.

00:55:38.130 --> 00:55:40.770
And since he's
been President, it

00:55:40.770 --> 00:55:42.020
seems to me he's gotten worse.

00:55:42.020 --> 00:55:43.150
Do you think that's true?

00:55:43.150 --> 00:55:43.900
RUTH SHERMAN: Yes.

00:55:43.900 --> 00:55:44.480
He has.

00:55:44.480 --> 00:55:50.040
And I think that Obama was
a great reader of scripts.

00:55:50.040 --> 00:55:52.380
He's a great reader of
scripts on the teleprompter.

00:55:52.380 --> 00:55:53.891
He's not great off the cuff.

00:55:53.891 --> 00:55:55.890
I mean, he knows how to
memorize a stump speech,

00:55:55.890 --> 00:55:58.360
and he knows how to get out
there and engage an audience.

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:01.491
But what ends up happening, and
this happens with all of them,

00:56:01.491 --> 00:56:01.990
by the way.

00:56:01.990 --> 00:56:03.240
It's not just Obama.

00:56:03.240 --> 00:56:04.650
We expected more
of him, I think,

00:56:04.650 --> 00:56:07.650
because he was so
wonderful as a speaker.

00:56:07.650 --> 00:56:10.070
Was so, like, whoa,
we'd been wandering

00:56:10.070 --> 00:56:13.170
in this desert of bad
communicators for too long.

00:56:13.170 --> 00:56:14.060
I had been.

00:56:14.060 --> 00:56:15.050
I don't know about you.

00:56:15.050 --> 00:56:17.240
I certainly had been.

00:56:17.240 --> 00:56:20.370
And then they do it
over and over again.

00:56:20.370 --> 00:56:21.450
It gets boring.

00:56:21.450 --> 00:56:23.950
It gets boring because
they don't do anything new.

00:56:23.950 --> 00:56:24.970
So--

00:56:24.970 --> 00:56:27.170
AUDIENCE: I think
a lot of us here,

00:56:27.170 --> 00:56:29.260
we don't give as many
presentations as you do,

00:56:29.260 --> 00:56:31.310
of course, or any of
these politicians.

00:56:31.310 --> 00:56:33.285
And then, at least,
what happens to me,

00:56:33.285 --> 00:56:36.060
and probably many of us here,
is that we, all of a sudden,

00:56:36.060 --> 00:56:39.472
are called upon by our manager--
hey, I want you to give a talk.

00:56:39.472 --> 00:56:41.180
Like this happened a
few weeks ago to me.

00:56:41.180 --> 00:56:44.330
All my managers said, would you
give a talk to these 200 people

00:56:44.330 --> 00:56:46.040
at this-- And like, oh, man.

00:56:46.040 --> 00:56:48.110
OK.

00:56:48.110 --> 00:56:50.230
How do you-- I'm out of
practice, so to speak.

00:56:50.230 --> 00:56:51.896
And like you said,
you need to practice.

00:56:51.896 --> 00:56:54.230
But then, we don't have
that many opportunities.

00:56:54.230 --> 00:56:56.484
So how do you get
practice without--

00:56:56.484 --> 00:56:58.900
so that you're ready for when
the moment comes, without --

00:56:58.900 --> 00:57:00.650
kind of like being a backup
quarterback, you know.

00:57:00.650 --> 00:57:01.990
RUTH SHERMAN: Totally get it.

00:57:01.990 --> 00:57:03.760
You get rusty, is
what you're saying.

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:05.630
You get rusty.

00:57:05.630 --> 00:57:07.330
I get rusty, too.

00:57:07.330 --> 00:57:09.900
My practice for this
started six weeks ago.

00:57:09.900 --> 00:57:11.270
I've done this presentation.

00:57:11.270 --> 00:57:12.650
I'm a professional speaker.

00:57:12.650 --> 00:57:14.280
I speak all the time.

00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:16.000
But I started six weeks ago.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:19.490
I had notice, of course, and
started putting it together.

00:57:19.490 --> 00:57:21.779
Every four years it changes.

00:57:21.779 --> 00:57:23.320
And then, the last
couple of weeks, I

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:24.860
said it out loud every day.

00:57:24.860 --> 00:57:25.360
Every day.

00:57:25.360 --> 00:57:26.734
Because when you
say it out loud,

00:57:26.734 --> 00:57:29.330
just-- And I know you don't
get that same kind of notice.

00:57:29.330 --> 00:57:31.637
I'd like to know how
much time you did have.

00:57:31.637 --> 00:57:32.470
AUDIENCE: Two weeks.

00:57:32.470 --> 00:57:33.180
RUTH SHERMAN: You had two weeks?

00:57:33.180 --> 00:57:33.440
OK.

00:57:33.440 --> 00:57:34.300
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:34.300 --> 00:57:35.008
RUTH SHERMAN: OK.

00:57:35.008 --> 00:57:35.946
It's not ideal.

00:57:35.946 --> 00:57:36.570
It's not ideal.

00:57:36.570 --> 00:57:37.430
But it's something.

00:57:37.430 --> 00:57:39.263
How long was the presentation?

00:57:39.263 --> 00:57:40.230
AUDIENCE: 15 minutes.

00:57:40.230 --> 00:57:41.110
RUTH SHERMAN: OK.

00:57:41.110 --> 00:57:47.880
So think of it-- So let me just
give you the words per minute

00:57:47.880 --> 00:57:48.900
calculation.

00:57:48.900 --> 00:57:51.960
We speak at about
140 words per minute.

00:57:51.960 --> 00:57:56.690
And a 15-minute talk, then,
just do the math on that.

00:57:56.690 --> 00:58:00.150
So like, 2,000 words,
or 1,500 words,

00:58:00.150 --> 00:58:01.520
something of that nature.

00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:03.630
And you're not going
to write it all out.

00:58:03.630 --> 00:58:05.960
But as you say it, you've
got to practice it.

00:58:05.960 --> 00:58:10.040
And you can use a speaker clock,
like I have, to time yourself.

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:11.360
And you can use notes.

00:58:11.360 --> 00:58:13.730
I'm using notes
today, everybody.

00:58:13.730 --> 00:58:16.740
I'm looking at my
speaker's notes on here.

00:58:16.740 --> 00:58:19.350
There's no law against that.

00:58:19.350 --> 00:58:21.520
Are you allowed to
use notes, or slides?

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:22.860
OK, good.

00:58:22.860 --> 00:58:23.470
So, yeah.

00:58:23.470 --> 00:58:24.730
Just use your notes.

00:58:24.730 --> 00:58:25.990
But practice enough.

00:58:25.990 --> 00:58:28.530
I mean, if you've got
a week to do this,

00:58:28.530 --> 00:58:30.840
then you're going to have
to get to work quickly.

00:58:30.840 --> 00:58:32.080
AUDIENCE: Practice by
yourself, you mean?

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:32.450
RUTH SHERMAN: Yup.

00:58:32.450 --> 00:58:33.450
AUDIENCE: With a video camera?

00:58:33.450 --> 00:58:35.377
RUTH SHERMAN: You could
use a video camera,

00:58:35.377 --> 00:58:37.710
but if it's going to be too
much of a pain in the neck--

00:58:37.710 --> 00:58:38.760
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:39.730
RUTH SHERMAN:
Yeah, well even so.

00:58:39.730 --> 00:58:40.420
Yeah.

00:58:40.420 --> 00:58:42.920
If it's going to be too much
of a pain in the neck to set it

00:58:42.920 --> 00:58:44.450
up and get that going.

00:58:44.450 --> 00:58:46.840
And if you're not going to
watch it, then don't bother.

00:58:46.840 --> 00:58:48.900
And that's the biggest thing.

00:58:48.900 --> 00:58:52.040
It's very painful to
watch yourself on video.

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:54.870
It's like 100 times more
painful than listening to your

00:58:54.870 --> 00:58:57.110
voicemail. [LAUGHS] Right?

00:58:57.110 --> 00:58:59.245
It's terrible.

00:58:59.245 --> 00:59:00.870
And even my celebrity
clients are like,

00:59:00.870 --> 00:59:04.560
oh, god, don't show me-- It's
like, you gotta watch yourself.

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:09.220
But if it's going to stop you
from practicing, don't bother.

00:59:09.220 --> 00:59:10.950
Don't bother.

00:59:10.950 --> 00:59:12.800
It's ideal if you
could do it that way,

00:59:12.800 --> 00:59:14.540
but only if you're
going to watch it.

00:59:14.540 --> 00:59:16.120
But saying it out
loud is the key.

00:59:16.120 --> 00:59:18.740
What you'll also find, and this
is something I didn't mention.

00:59:18.740 --> 00:59:22.180
When you say it out loud
enough, the speech centers

00:59:22.180 --> 00:59:23.740
in your brain are activated.

00:59:23.740 --> 00:59:27.350
And things that you didn't
even consider to say,

00:59:27.350 --> 00:59:29.030
like all kinds of
pithy things, come

00:59:29.030 --> 00:59:31.310
to mind that you
wouldn't have considered.

00:59:31.310 --> 00:59:33.476
So keep that in mind.

00:59:33.476 --> 00:59:35.100
So saying it out
loud, and you probably

00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:37.474
have to say it out loud every
day, probably several times

00:59:37.474 --> 00:59:38.070
a day.

00:59:38.070 --> 00:59:42.250
Another tip is to not always
start at the beginning.

00:59:42.250 --> 00:59:44.910
Because then, of course,
you get interrupted,

00:59:44.910 --> 00:59:47.010
and you put it down,
and then what happens?

00:59:47.010 --> 00:59:49.410
You come back, and you start
again at the beginning.

00:59:49.410 --> 00:59:50.690
And the beginning's great.

00:59:50.690 --> 00:59:52.850
And the middle and the end suck.

00:59:52.850 --> 00:59:53.880
They do.

00:59:53.880 --> 00:59:54.630
It's what happens.

00:59:54.630 --> 00:59:57.240
You have to start in the
middle sometimes, and take it

00:59:57.240 --> 01:00:01.300
to the end, or go over some
chunks that are troublesome.

01:00:01.300 --> 01:00:03.240
See how the words
roll off your tongue.

01:00:03.240 --> 01:00:07.084
AUDIENCE: One thing I've been
practicing-- [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:07.084 --> 01:00:10.200
I think one thing that I've
been practicing, after watching

01:00:10.200 --> 01:00:13.430
myself do this presentation,
which was, let's say,

01:00:13.430 --> 01:00:17.686
less than optimal, I realized
I speak really quickly.

01:00:17.686 --> 01:00:19.310
And then, now I'm
trying to actually do

01:00:19.310 --> 01:00:20.480
that in everyday life.

01:00:20.480 --> 01:00:24.000
And so, how do you apply your
techniques from presentations

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.460
that you give to hundreds
or thousands of people,

01:00:26.460 --> 01:00:31.352
to kind of groups of
one to three or four?

01:00:31.352 --> 01:00:32.810
RUTH SHERMAN: Well,
I will tell you

01:00:32.810 --> 01:00:36.590
that I also have the problem
of speaking too fast,

01:00:36.590 --> 01:00:39.600
and it's a constant tape that's
playing in the back of my head

01:00:39.600 --> 01:00:42.300
to modulate my rate.

01:00:42.300 --> 01:00:47.280
So I used to, on my notes, put
a big "slow down," slow down,

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:48.270
on every page.

01:00:48.270 --> 01:00:50.770
And then it became wallpaper,
and I had to change the color,

01:00:50.770 --> 01:00:52.270
or change the-- right?

01:00:52.270 --> 01:00:54.490
You blank it out after a while.

01:00:54.490 --> 01:00:58.730
So I give myself some
kind of a tip, or helper,

01:00:58.730 --> 01:01:01.700
or some kind of a
cue, that enables

01:01:01.700 --> 01:01:04.200
me to pay attention to that.

01:01:04.200 --> 01:01:05.680
And then, after
you do it enough,

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:11.610
and you see how slowing down
enables you to think better.

01:01:11.610 --> 01:01:15.370
It enables you to think better,
and come up, and then entertain

01:01:15.370 --> 01:01:17.960
questions, and not
get, perhaps, flustered

01:01:17.960 --> 01:01:20.270
if you make a mistake, or
you're reading the room,

01:01:20.270 --> 01:01:21.740
and things aren't
going that well.

01:01:21.740 --> 01:01:22.810
Or you think they're not.

01:01:22.810 --> 01:01:24.230
You imagine they're
not going well.

01:01:24.230 --> 01:01:26.605
I mean, just because people
aren't looking at you doesn't

01:01:26.605 --> 01:01:28.430
mean they're not going well.

01:01:28.430 --> 01:01:31.320
But those are some of
the things that I do,

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:32.410
and that I've tried to do.

01:01:32.410 --> 01:01:34.490
And then, the more you do
it, the better you get.

01:01:34.490 --> 01:01:37.890
Which is another reason, I
think, to do it more regularly,

01:01:37.890 --> 01:01:41.750
and join a-- do
more Toastmasters.

01:01:41.750 --> 01:01:44.990
Have more opportunities,
and volunteer more

01:01:44.990 --> 01:01:45.860
for opportunities.

01:01:45.860 --> 01:01:47.260
If you're not, it's a pain.

01:01:47.260 --> 01:01:47.910
It's hard work.

01:01:47.910 --> 01:01:49.610
It's hard to get good at this.

01:01:49.610 --> 01:01:51.180
So that's another,
it's an addition.

01:01:51.180 --> 01:01:53.450
But then it's like
riding a bike.

01:01:53.450 --> 01:01:55.220
You get it, and you've
got it, and then

01:01:55.220 --> 01:01:59.220
you only have to, like we said
earlier, just, when you get

01:01:59.220 --> 01:02:00.930
rusty, and you just refresh.

01:02:00.930 --> 01:02:03.035
You refresh.

01:02:03.035 --> 01:02:04.910
AUDIENCE: I noticed,
started paying attention

01:02:04.910 --> 01:02:09.060
to your hand gestures
after you called them out.

01:02:09.060 --> 01:02:12.760
And no doubt you
must practice them.

01:02:12.760 --> 01:02:13.450
No.

01:02:13.450 --> 01:02:14.130
RUTH SHERMAN: I'm
just very animated

01:02:14.130 --> 01:02:15.296
AUDIENCE: That's surprising.

01:02:15.296 --> 01:02:16.880
RUTH SHERMAN: I'm
just very animated.

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:17.380
Yeah.

01:02:17.380 --> 01:02:20.820
And not everybody has to
be as animated as I am.

01:02:20.820 --> 01:02:24.500
AUDIENCE: So that they-- do
they come naturally to you?

01:02:24.500 --> 01:02:27.860
Or is there a set of
particular hand gestures

01:02:27.860 --> 01:02:29.370
that work better than others?

01:02:29.370 --> 01:02:32.590
Or ones that you recommend
for people that it does not

01:02:32.590 --> 01:02:33.780
come naturally to?

01:02:33.780 --> 01:02:34.500
RUTH SHERMAN: OK.

01:02:34.500 --> 01:02:39.970
So, I think maybe that answer
I gave you was too flip.

01:02:39.970 --> 01:02:41.790
That, no, I don't practice.

01:02:41.790 --> 01:02:44.000
Of course, over the
years I've worked on it.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:45.700
All of this is technique.

01:02:45.700 --> 01:02:46.690
It's technique.

01:02:46.690 --> 01:02:49.570
It's as if you're learning a
golf swing, or a tennis swing,

01:02:49.570 --> 01:02:52.940
or you're learning to
play a musical instrument.

01:02:52.940 --> 01:02:54.490
You're learning technique.

01:02:54.490 --> 01:02:55.870
And that's what this is.

01:02:55.870 --> 01:02:59.620
So one of the techniques that
I learned, in terms of hands,

01:02:59.620 --> 01:03:02.659
is keeping them
below-- you know,

01:03:02.659 --> 01:03:04.450
not waving them around
in front of my face.

01:03:04.450 --> 01:03:06.450
Not having them
up here too much.

01:03:06.450 --> 01:03:08.640
If I'm on a stage,
like I am now.

01:03:08.640 --> 01:03:11.960
A stage, an ish,
a platform, where

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:14.700
I have more physical
space and latitude,

01:03:14.700 --> 01:03:15.960
I can be more expansive.

01:03:15.960 --> 01:03:18.700
If I'm on a video, I
have to keep it smaller.

01:03:18.700 --> 01:03:21.110
It's one of the problems
that Bernie Sanders, I think,

01:03:21.110 --> 01:03:23.780
had when he was at
the Democratic debate.

01:03:23.780 --> 01:03:26.690
I'll be very interested to
see what he does tomorrow.

01:03:26.690 --> 01:03:29.010
I'll be very interested
to see if he pulls it

01:03:29.010 --> 01:03:30.519
in a little bit for TV.

01:03:30.519 --> 01:03:31.310
Which is different.

01:03:31.310 --> 01:03:32.260
It's a box.

01:03:32.260 --> 01:03:38.790
But keeping them lower, using
them to enhance my words,

01:03:38.790 --> 01:03:41.470
to give meaning to my
words, because they do that.

01:03:41.470 --> 01:03:44.120
And then also not
doing things like this,

01:03:44.120 --> 01:03:45.290
or putting them in pockets.

01:03:45.290 --> 01:03:46.870
Pockets are dangerous.

01:03:46.870 --> 01:03:47.580
They really are.

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:48.210
They're dangerous.

01:03:48.210 --> 01:03:49.501
Or putting them behind my back.

01:03:52.300 --> 01:03:54.340
Or like this.

01:03:54.340 --> 01:03:56.750
They call this fig leaf.

01:03:56.750 --> 01:03:57.455
Fig leaf.

01:03:57.455 --> 01:03:58.110
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:58.110 --> 01:03:58.910
RUTH SHERMAN: All right?

01:03:58.910 --> 01:04:00.890
Next time you watch a
politician at the podium,

01:04:00.890 --> 01:04:03.090
watch all the aids
standing there like this.

01:04:03.090 --> 01:04:04.920
Fig leaf.

01:04:04.920 --> 01:04:07.810
So these are, yeah, so those
are some things not to do.

01:04:07.810 --> 01:04:11.140
And just watch how
you move your hands

01:04:11.140 --> 01:04:13.320
in your one-on-one
conversations,

01:04:13.320 --> 01:04:16.920
your informal Google
conversations,

01:04:16.920 --> 01:04:20.300
as you're moving through
your daily life here.

01:04:20.300 --> 01:04:21.170
And elsewhere.

01:04:21.170 --> 01:04:23.220
I guarantee you, you use them.

01:04:23.220 --> 01:04:25.990
You just have to bring
that to the stage.

01:04:25.990 --> 01:04:28.430
AUDIENCE: Are you are
techniques universal,

01:04:28.430 --> 01:04:31.370
or are they just for
the American culture?

01:04:31.370 --> 01:04:32.880
Would this work in Brazil?

01:04:32.880 --> 01:04:34.120
RUTH SHERMAN: Great question!

01:04:34.120 --> 01:04:35.730
Yes.

01:04:35.730 --> 01:04:38.680
This is American
business speech culture

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:40.300
that we're talking about today.

01:04:40.300 --> 01:04:41.705
For sure.

01:04:41.705 --> 01:04:45.180
It is different in other
cultures, as many of you

01:04:45.180 --> 01:04:46.490
already know.

01:04:46.490 --> 01:04:46.990
OK?

01:04:46.990 --> 01:04:49.453
So what is your native country?

01:04:49.453 --> 01:04:50.240
AUDIENCE: India.

01:04:50.240 --> 01:04:50.948
RUTH SHERMAN: OK.

01:04:50.948 --> 01:04:53.220
So it's going to be
different in India.

01:04:53.220 --> 01:04:54.720
It's going to be
different in India.

01:04:54.720 --> 01:04:57.370
It's going to be different
even in other English-speaking

01:04:57.370 --> 01:04:58.220
countries.

01:04:58.220 --> 01:04:59.090
Different in the UK.

01:04:59.090 --> 01:05:00.200
Different in Canada.

01:05:00.200 --> 01:05:04.490
Although Canadian speakers
are very, very similar

01:05:04.490 --> 01:05:06.970
to US business speakers.

01:05:06.970 --> 01:05:07.620
But yes.

01:05:07.620 --> 01:05:09.630
So I guess what
I would say here,

01:05:09.630 --> 01:05:14.010
if you are speaking in the US,
you have to-- when in Rome,

01:05:14.010 --> 01:05:16.670
as they say, do
what the Romans do.

01:05:16.670 --> 01:05:20.050
And if you go back
and speak in India,

01:05:20.050 --> 01:05:22.740
or elsewhere, make sure
you do your homework,

01:05:22.740 --> 01:05:25.520
and see what it is they're
going to find appealing,

01:05:25.520 --> 01:05:27.710
and what it is they're
going to find off-putting.

01:05:27.710 --> 01:05:28.870
That's what I have to do.

01:05:28.870 --> 01:05:30.195
And I get in trouble.

01:05:30.195 --> 01:05:31.500
I get in trouble.

01:05:31.500 --> 01:05:37.560
AUDIENCE: What do you suggest we
should do if, when you can see

01:05:37.560 --> 01:05:38.727
you're losing your audience?

01:05:38.727 --> 01:05:39.643
RUTH SHERMAN: Oh, god.

01:05:39.643 --> 01:05:40.940
That's an awful feeling.

01:05:40.940 --> 01:05:42.310
AUDIENCE: Yeah, do you have
any tips or suggestions

01:05:42.310 --> 01:05:43.940
on how you can bring them back?

01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:47.670
RUTH SHERMAN: OK, my
first tip-- [LAUGHS] Yeah.

01:05:47.670 --> 01:05:51.370
One of the things that
you have to do beforehand,

01:05:51.370 --> 01:05:53.430
you can prevent
losing your audience.

01:05:53.430 --> 01:05:54.620
You can.

01:05:54.620 --> 01:05:59.330
By making sure that your
content has what we call rhythm.

01:05:59.330 --> 01:06:08.090
Rhythm is the interspersing of
stories, quotes, statistics,

01:06:08.090 --> 01:06:13.390
funny things that happen to
you, or have happened to you.

01:06:13.390 --> 01:06:15.500
And they happen to
us on a daily basis.

01:06:15.500 --> 01:06:20.446
Or an interesting
article that you read.

01:06:20.446 --> 01:06:23.000
Any kind of public
information that you

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:25.280
can bring in to
your presentation,

01:06:25.280 --> 01:06:28.520
and interspersing it
throughout the presentation.

01:06:28.520 --> 01:06:32.200
Because if the presentation is
all theory, all theoretical,

01:06:32.200 --> 01:06:36.960
or all data, all technical,
you will lose your audience.

01:06:36.960 --> 01:06:37.880
You will.

01:06:37.880 --> 01:06:40.380
I don't care where you're
working, or what you're doing.

01:06:40.380 --> 01:06:42.570
As human beings, this
is how we connect.

01:06:42.570 --> 01:06:45.210
And there are ways to make
your information come alive,

01:06:45.210 --> 01:06:46.920
and in how people enjoy it.

01:06:46.920 --> 01:06:50.679
What I did today was, I
don't have it in color.

01:06:50.679 --> 01:06:51.970
I don't have my notes in color.

01:06:51.970 --> 01:06:54.440
I color-code my outline.

01:06:54.440 --> 01:06:58.650
My outline is my points,
the theory, the data,

01:06:58.650 --> 01:07:00.910
the boring stuff.

01:07:00.910 --> 01:07:01.920
OK?

01:07:01.920 --> 01:07:05.390
All the stuff that turns me on
and turns everybody else off

01:07:05.390 --> 01:07:06.470
is in yellow.

01:07:06.470 --> 01:07:07.830
Highlighted in yellow.

01:07:07.830 --> 01:07:09.590
The stories are in pink.

01:07:09.590 --> 01:07:14.550
And the applications, show of
hands, audience participation.

01:07:14.550 --> 01:07:17.310
Maybe I'll put a video up there,
or I'll tell a funny story

01:07:17.310 --> 01:07:18.310
and get people to laugh.

01:07:18.310 --> 01:07:21.410
Where people are physically
engaged in some way,

01:07:21.410 --> 01:07:22.570
that's in green.

01:07:22.570 --> 01:07:27.580
If I see everything, there's too
much yellow, I gotta change it,

01:07:27.580 --> 01:07:31.000
because I know I'm going
to lose the audience.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:32.040
So that's what you do.

01:07:32.040 --> 01:07:34.170
You want to prevent
it to begin with.

01:07:34.170 --> 01:07:36.310
The second thing
that you want to do

01:07:36.310 --> 01:07:38.580
is, if you do see
people falling asleep,

01:07:38.580 --> 01:07:41.597
doing other things, not engaged,
their body language, whatever

01:07:41.597 --> 01:07:44.876
is going wrong, or you
think it's going wrong,

01:07:44.876 --> 01:07:47.390
maybe it's not your fault.
Maybe they had a bad night.

01:07:47.390 --> 01:07:50.950
Maybe the baby kept them up
all night, or they're sick,

01:07:50.950 --> 01:07:54.350
or they've just had a bad
phone call before they

01:07:54.350 --> 01:07:57.530
came into your meeting, and, you
know, something's going badly.

01:07:57.530 --> 01:08:00.520
So it's not always your
fault. I kind of try

01:08:00.520 --> 01:08:05.440
to go there, when I feel
like I'm losing an audience.

01:08:05.440 --> 01:08:07.690
But I think you can prevent
it, for the most part.

01:08:07.690 --> 01:08:10.437
And that was a
huge lesson for me.

01:08:10.437 --> 01:08:12.520
Because just like everybody
else, all that theory,

01:08:12.520 --> 01:08:15.260
all that theoretical
stuff, you know,

01:08:15.260 --> 01:08:17.680
how to breathe to give
a good speaking voice.

01:08:17.680 --> 01:08:19.140
It's like, no.

01:08:19.140 --> 01:08:20.240
No, don't.

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:23.399
I hired a coach to help me.

01:08:23.399 --> 01:08:24.380
No, you can't say that.

01:08:24.380 --> 01:08:25.930
It's boring.

01:08:25.930 --> 01:08:27.160
OK.

01:08:27.160 --> 01:08:28.097
So it's a big lesson.

01:08:28.097 --> 01:08:28.930
